@MastersThesis{Kerth2007,
  Title                    = {Gene für das Paarungsverhalten bei drei singenden Heuschreckenarten: Chorthippus biguttulus, C. brunneus und C. mollis - ein Vergleich von Kandidatengenen mit Kontrollgenen},
  Author                   = {Claudius Kerth},
  School                   = {Universität Erlangen-Nürnberg},
  Year                     = {2007},
  Month                    = {October},

  Abstract                 = {The three closely related grasshopper species C. biguttulus, C. brunneus and C. mollis occur sympatrically over large portions of Europe. They belong to the C. biguttulus species group (Orthoptera, Acrididae) whose members have been shown to be almost exclusively isolated by the acoustic communication system of the male calling song and female preference for the conspecific song. Nevertheless, occasional breakdown of the behavioural isolation between these species still occurs, creating conspicuous hybrid populations. It is therefore assumed that strong selection is acting against the introgression of foreign song and preference genes, especially as male hybrids are behaviourally sterile. Thus, genes for mating behaviour should be distinguished from other genes by a stronger differentiation in the three species. To date, RFLP studies of the mitochondrial genome and allozyme studies have shown no genetic differentiation among any member of the C. biguttulus species group. For this reason, I investigated the genetic divergence of the three grasshopper species at a candidate gene locus for mating behaviour (cacophony) as well as at two housekeeping genes (aconitase and tropomyosin).
As opposed to the housekeeping genes, the candidate gene cacophony shows a strong and significant differentiation between C. biguttulus and C. brunneus (Nei's D: 1.97, p<0.001). Even though all mutations in the 892 analysed base pairs of the cacophony mRNA coding sequence are silent (i. e. synonymous), the extremely low nucleotide diversity (?T: 0.001) suggests strong selection at genetically linked loci (e.g. regulatory sequences of cacophony). Moreover, a comparison of sequences from males and females strongly suggests an X-chromosomal location of cacophony in the studied grasshopper species. The housekeeping gene aconitase shows a strong and significant differentiation of C. mollis against the other two species (FCT: 0.46, 95% CI above 0.36) and only a minor differentiation of C. biguttulus and C. brunneus (FCT: 0.076, 95% CI above 0.045). The housekeeping gene tropomyosin only weakly differentiates C. mollis from the two other species (FCT: 0.065, 95% CI above 0.021).
Along with the recently published fruitless gene, cacophony and aconitase are the first significantly differentiated loci to be found in the C. biguttulus species group. No geographic structuring of the genetic variation at the three investigated loci could be detected. Furthermore, I found no significant deviation from neutral evolution at the aconitase locus in the three species (Tajima's D test), qualifying aconitase as a neutral marker for further genetic studies in the C. biguttulus species group.},
